fields.title: About us
fields.content:
The company

easySPSS was born 20 years ago in Ireland, where only a few knew SPSS and it was used mainly to do basic analysis and reports for research purposes.

The company has since expanded both geographically, operating worldwide for the past 5 years, and in the range of products and services offered, including the technical support online functionality that has been helping SPSS users since 2010.

easySPSS are a certified IBM SPSS Online Software Reseller and Support Provider. We have been awarded "Reseller of the year" for the past 6 years.



The Team

We are a team of people with very different backgrounds, brought together by our passion about Technology and Analytics.

Our Sales Team know that one size doesn't fit all, that's why they will work with you to find a solution that suits you.

Our Tech Support Team are experts on what they do and they will work with you to solve any technical difficulty you might have.



Remember, our mission is to give you exactly what you need, at the best value.

author: admin@admin.com
fields.title: Customising Toolbars in IBM SPSS Statistics
fields.content:
Learn how to customize existing toolbars and create new ones to launch frequently used procedures and generate graphs and charts with the click of a toolbar button.

To create a custom tool to open a file, to run a command syntax file, or to run a script:
• Click New Tool in the Edit Toolbar dialog box
• Enter a descriptive label for the tool
• Select the action you want for the tool (open a file, run a command syntax file, or run a script)
• Click Browse to select a file or application to associate with the tool
• New tools are displayed in the User-Defined category, which also contains user-defined menu items

author: admin@admin.com
fields.title: Identifying Duplicate Cases in IBM SPSS Statistics
fields.content:
Cleaning a dataset can be tricky, especially when it comes to duplicate cases. This function helps you to define duplicate cases in any way you want and flag them to be deleted or used as desired.

To identify and flag duplicate cases:
- Select Data from the menu
- Select Identify Duplicate Cases
- This opens the Identify Duplicate Cases Dialog Box "Identify Duplicate Cases"
- Select one or more variables that identify matching cases and move them to the Define matching cases by box
- Select an appropriate option in the Variables to Create section 
- Finally, select one or more variables to sort cases, or automatically filter the duplicate cases, so they won't be included in reports, charts, or calculations of statistics

author: admin@admin.com
fields.title: What makes a good Data Analyst?
fields.content:
A lot of organisations have invested money in tools. Having the right tools is required but not sufficient. Investing in the people who use the tools is much more important! The challenge is that good analysts can be hard to come.

Here are the 8 pointers every analyst should strive to develop:
1. Be able to tell a story, but keep it Simple
2.  Pay attention to Detail
3. Be Commercially Savvy
4. Be Creative with Data
5.  Be a People Person
6. Keep Learning new Tools and Skills
7.  Don’t be Afraid to make Mistakes, Learn from Them
8.  Know when to Stop

We want to hear your comment below. We want to hear what pointers you think a good analyst should strive to develop.

author: admin@admin.com
fields.title: 7 Tips for Transitioning Data Insights into Business as Usual
fields.content:
The Irish playwright was on the money – no matter what way you look at it, attacking an old problem with a new solution is going to require change. In particular, attacking an old problem with advanced predictive analytics is going to spur an array of changes to business processes and with this, a necessary change of perspective. Staff will now be tasked with using the results of models to prioritise who they target with marketing materials, who they call and which products they promote to them. In times of transition, staff can feel overwhelmed, confused and frustrated if communication is poor. In fact lack of staff buy-in is one of the top reasons for the failure of newly adopted predictive analytics solutions.

1. Start small, talk business
2. Include the business from the beginning
3. Identify obstacles
4. Make a clear deployment plan
5. Keep the analysts involved
6. Prioritise good communication
7. Know when to stop

author: admin@admin.com
fields.title: Commentary and Annotations in IBM SPSS Modeler
fields.content:
Add comments, document your thoughts and share details directly on the canvas with this sticky notes-like feature.

1. Select the node(s) you wish to attach to the note or opt for standalone note.
2. Right click and choose ‘New Comment’ and click on the icon to “edit the properties of the current stream.”
3. Choose the ‘Text’ row and select “Custom colours” 
4. You can choose the colour!
5. The comment box is now coloured with the colour of your choice.
